title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix. We call an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex> an <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Inverse</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> if
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}\mathbf {B}=\mathbf {B}\mathbf {A}=\mathbf {I}_{n}.]]></fr:tex>
In this case, we call <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Invertible</html:dfn> (or <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Nonsingular</html:dfn>).</fr:p><fr:p>Otherwise, if no such <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex> exists, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> is called a <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Noninvertible</html:dfn> (or <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Singular</html:dfn>) matrix.</fr:p>
 
   
